SIMPLE: turnover
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turnover
<hw>Turn"o`ver</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucir⟧rn"⟦omac⟧`v⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or result of turning over; an upset; <as>as, a
bad <ex>turnover</ex> in a carriage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A semicircular pie or tart made by turning one half
of a circular crust over the other, inclosing the fruit or other
materials; <as>as, an apple <ex>turnover</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An apprentice, in any trade, who is handed over from
one master to another to complete his time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turnover</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Turnover
<hw>Turn"o`ver</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Admitting of being turned over;
made to be turned over; <as>as, a <ex>turnover</ex> collar,
etc</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turnpike</ent>⟦br⟧
